 } rec_coords;
 
 
+/*! @brief Struct for holding equatorial coordinates.
+ *
+ *  Equatorial coordinates are composed of right ascension and declination.  Both
+ *  are expressed in radians.
+ */
+typedef struct {
+    double ra;                 /*!< @brief The right ascension, in radians. */
+    double dec;                /*!< @brief The declination, in radians. */
+} equatorial_coords;
+
+/*! @brief Struct for holding ecliptical coordinates.
+ *
+ *  Ecliptical coordinates are composed of ecliptical latitude and ecliptical
+ *  longitude.  They represent the heliocentic position of a body with respect
+ *  to the plane of the ecliptic.
+ */
+typedef struct {
+    double ecl_lat;            /*!< @brief The ecliptical latitude, in radians.  */
+    double ecl_lon;            /*!< @brief The ecliptical longitude, in radians. */
+} ecliptical_coords;
+

+/*! @brief Struct for holding horizon coordinates.
+ *
+ *  Horizon coordinates are composed of altitude and azimuth, the
+ *  geocentric coordinates at which an observer will see an object in
+ *  the sky.  Altitude is the angle between the horizon and the
+ *  zenith.  Azimuth is the angle measured anti-clockwise from North.
+ */
+typedef struct {
+    double altitude;  /*!< @brief The altitude, in radians. */
+    double azimuth;   /*!< @brief The azimuth, in radians.  */
+} horizon_coords;
+
+/*! @brief Struct for holding geographic coordinates of an observer.
+ *
+ *  Geographic coordinates specify the geographic position at which an
+ *  observer is standing to observe something in the sky.  Latitude and
+ *  longitude are both measured in radians.
+ */
+typedef struct {
+    double latitude;   /*!< @brief The latitude, in radians. */
+    double longitude;  /*!< @brief The longitude, in radians. */
+} geographic_coords;
+

  *  are moving to a new universe.

+    const double T = ephJdToJCent(jd);

 }

 /*! @brief Converts a date in the Julian or Gregorian calendars to the
  *  Julian Day Number (Meeus 7.1).
  *
- *  @param[in] yr        Year, 2BC is -1, 1BC is 0, 1AD is 1, 1998AD is 1998, etc.
- *  @param[in] mo        Month, with January being 1, February 2, etc.
- *  @param[in] dy        Day, may be fractional day.  1 is the first day of the month.
- *  @param[in] gregorian If true, use the Gregorian calendar, else use
- *                       Julian calendar.
+ *  @param[in] calDate   The calendar date to convert to a Julian Day number.
  *
  *  @return              The julian day number that matches the calendar
  *                       date provided.
  */
-double ephCalToJd(int yr, int mo, double dy, EPH_Bool gregorian)
+double ephCalToJd(const EPH_CalDate calDate)
 {
-    if (mo <= 2) {
-	yr--;
-	mo += 12;
+    EPH_CalDate working;
+    working = calDate;
+    if (working.month <= 2) {
+	working.year--;
+	working.month += 12;
     }
 
     int B;
-    if (gregorian) {
-	const int A = yr / 100;
+    if (working.gregorian) {
+	const int A = working.year / 100;

 	B = 0;
     }
-    return (int) (365.25 * (yr + 4716)) + (int) (30.6001 * (mo + 1)) + dy +
+    return (int) (365.25 * (working.year + 4716)) + (int) (30.6001 * (working.month + 1)) + working.day +
 	B - 1524.5;
 }

 }
 
+/*! @brief Converts spherical VSOP coordinates for the date to coordinates for
+ *  a particular epoch.
+ *
+ *  Given a set of spherical coordinates for a body that refer to the position
+ *  using heliocentric ecliptic coordinates for the epoch of the particular date, this
+ *  function will convert the coordinates to ones of a requested epoch.  This is
+ *  done by applying rules of precession.
+ *
+ *  One particular use for this function is to be able to use VSOP elements
+ *  for the epoch of the date to get a J2000.0 epoch, which is necessary when
+ *  calculating the solar position for various cometary orbits, and the like.
+ *
+ *  @param[in] vsc          The spherical coordinates to convert.
+ *  @param[in] epochJd      The epoch to which the coordinates should be converted.
+ *  @param[in] dateJd       The date for which the coordinates have been calculated.
+ *
+ *  @return A set of spherical coordinates, adjusted by precession for the specified epoch.
+ */
+EPH_VsopSphCoords ephVsopDateToEpoch(const EPH_VsopSphCoords vsc, double epochJd, double dateJd)
+{
+    EPH_VsopSphCoords output = vsc;
 
+    /* Stop right here if the incoming coordinates are in an error state. */
+    if (output.error_state != ok) {
+	return output;
+    }
 
+    /* Make sure that these coordinates are spherical for date. */
+    if(output.vh.version != hel_sph_date) {
+      output.error_state = wrong_source;
+      return output;
+    }
+
+    /* Adjust for the precession between the date of the coordinates, and the
+       requested epoch. */
+
+    ephPrecessionEcl(
+        ephPrecessionGetElementsEcl(epochJd, dateJd),
+        output.sc.ecl,
+        &output.sc.ecl
+        );
+
+    return output;
+}
+
+
+
 /*! @brief Converts spherical geocentric coordinates of the Sun to
  *  rectangular geocentric coordinates of the Sun.
  *

             EPH_EclipticalCoords tempecl;
